post_text:
While we can't undo the damage from this crisis, we can do something to help. If you and your family have been spared from the worst of this crisis, we are asking you to consider giving to our Great Oaks Legacy Community Support Fund. Every dollar we raise towards this fund will be sent back out as small grants to members of our GOLCS family students and staff who are experiencing hardships resulting from this crisis.

The easiest way to support families with urgent needs is by making a gift through Paypal today via our website:

greatoakslegacy.org/ways-to-support.

Thank you in advance for anything you can give.

post_text: The vision of Great Oaks Legacy Charter School is for its graduates to lead Newark to become a transcendent city in our nation and world—a model city where all children have access to the highest quality education and constant interaction with exemplar adults, which, in turn, prepares each and every child to fulfill his or her greatest dreams—dreams that further strengthen the moral, cultural, and intellectual fabric of Newark.

Great Oaks Legacy is open to all students! We are a free, public charter school open to students in the city of Newark and neighboring districts.

Families that missed the initial application window or who are unsatisfied with their application results have the opportunity to match directly or be placed on our waitlist via the Newark Enrolls system.

Visit newarkenrolls.org today!

Our families need help and we are seeking emergency assistance to support them. Help us reach our goal of $50,000 to assist those most affected by COVID-19.

In a recent survey, many of our students’ parents shared concerns about affording groceries and household products as well as masks and gloves to protect themselves. Others expressed that they’d lost loved ones to this illness.

While we can't undo the damage from this crisis, we can do something to help. If you and your family have been spared from the worst of this crisis, we are asking you to consider giving to our Great Oaks Legacy Community Support Fund. Every dollar we raise towards this fund will be sent back out as small grants to members of our GOLCS family students and staff who are experiencing hardships resulting from this crisis.

The easiest way to support families with urgent needs is by making a gift through Paypal today via our website: greatoakslegacy.org/ways-to-support.

Thank you in advance for anything you can give.

Teacher Appreciation Week continues with a shout out to Ms. Lockwood! What a star! 🤩“Thanks Ms. Lockwood for creating an awesome HMS video to inspire and motivate our students and their families during this time of remote learning! The video brought us to tears and meant so much to our community. Ms. Lockwood came up with a 4-minute video to let HMS students know how much they are missed by staff. She spent her time collecting pictures and videos from staff to create a video and shared it with students at our weekly community meeting. Students loved the video! We are so grateful for your thoughtfulness.”
#teacherappreciationweek #thankyouteachers #remotelearning

post_text:
Here’s another shining star to celebrate this Teacher Appreciation Week!

“Shout out to Ms. Domeville! Ms. Domeville is an amazing asset to our community and has gone above and beyond during our transition to remote learning in holding students accountable, creating student-centered, hands-on activities in ELA AND ART - projects and smaller assignments that are engaging and profoundly rigorous. She follows up with students and families every day, tutors students after the school day has ended, and works tirelessly to engage and support our KWLM. She's pushing our seniors to present independently, collaborate with peers in college level Socratic Seminars, and has designed projects that encourage them to brainstorm ways to have positive impacts on their community. We are so proud of the work Ms. Domeville has done and are beyond grateful for the tremendous impact she's had on our community.”

#teacherappreciationweek

Our DMS Dean, Mr. Cuffee received his mail ballot, and he’s following the Project Ready guide to fill it out correctly! To follow along, click here https://youtu.be/EVXCObkSfJk

If you have your ballot, there are 3 things to remember:
1. You can vote for up to three candidates!
2. Use pencil or blue or black pen to fill in the ovals.
3. Make sure you fill in the ovals ALL THE WAY. A partial fill-in could make your ballot invalid.

Still have other questions? Visit Project Ready’s website for more support https://www.newarkvotesbymail.com/

#newarkvotesbymail #newark #OaksVotes

Happy National Grilled Cheese Sandwich Day! Did you know that grilled cheese sandwiches are among one of the top comfort foods in the United States?
According to food historians, the modern version of the grilled cheese sandwich originated in the 1920's when inexpensive sliced bread and American cheese became easily available. Originally it was made as an open-faced sandwich.

#DidYouKnow #TheMoreYouKNow #NationalHolidays

post_text: Jordan Solomon is a member of the class of 2018, he is in his second year at The College of New Jersey in Ewing Township, NJ. Jordan is working on earning his Bachelor of Science in Computer Science. Computer science at TCNJ is hands-on, team-based, and project-centered—just like the real world. Take courses in exciting fields—artificial intelligence, computational biology, cloud computing—while collaborating across disciplines to solve real problems through computing. Jordan is also involved in the College Union Board (CUBS) which plans student events and community engagement programs, the Computer Science club, and Men of Excellence. The Men of Excellence organization focuses on academic and life issues of underrepresented males identifying from retention to economic empowerment.

Dear GOLCS Families,

Out of an abundance of caution, all Great Oaks Legacy campuses in Newark will be closed effective March 14th through March 29th.

On Monday, March 16th between the hours of 10AM and 12PM, students will be able to stop by their campus briefly to pick up breakfast and/or lunch and any work packets they may have not received yet. Note: There is no student drop off permitted, only pick up of food/materials.

Thank you in advance for your cooperation in this challenging time.

Breetny Jusma, a member of the class of 2019 is in her second semester at Montclair State University in Montclair, NJ. Breetny is in the process of earning her Bachelor of Arts in Sociology. She is currently involved in three student organizations: LadiesFIRST, the Haitian Student Association, the Brotherhood La Hermandad. The mission of LadiesFIRST is to overall teach self-worth and value through sisterhood, integrity, and love. The Haitian Student Association promotes the awareness, respect, and better understanding of Haitian history, culture, and traditions via social & cultural programs, designed to further educate the campus community and to help foster an atmosphere of cultural acceptance and diversity at Montclair State University.

We are proud of Breetny and wish her continued success #DrippinInSuccess #NewarkNJ #NewarkCharterSchool

post_text:
As black history month comes to a close, we recognize how black innovators, philosophers, artists, authors, athletes, educators, and even politicians have transformed our country. We understand that a month is not enough and the legacies of black history must continue to be told to share stories that can inspire us all.

Today as we prepare for Women’s History month, we recognize Shirley Chisholm who was the first black woman to be elected to the United States Congress and both the first woman and the first black person to run for the nomination of a major party for President of the United States.

#blackhistorymonth #blackhistorymonth2020 #blackhistory #shirleychisholm #president #campaign #politics #womenshistorymonth #womenshistory

post_text:
For Black History Month, we would like to recognize Hair Love - Oscar Award Winning animated short film that centers around the relationship between an African-American father Stephen and his daughter, Zuri and her hair. Despite having long locks, Stephen has been used to his wife doing his daughter's hair, so when she is unavailable right before a big event, Stephen will have to figure it out on his own. This sounds simple enough, but we soon come to find that Zuri's hair has a mind of its own.

post_text:
Today, we highlight Marley Dias, a young activist, feminist and founder of #1000BlackGirlBooks.

When Marley Dias was 11 years old, she was an avid reader but she grew tired of the books she was being given in school because they were all about white boys and their dogs so she was determined about changing that.

In November 2015, Dias launched a campaign #1000BlackGirlBooks and her goal was to collect and donate 1,000 books that feature black girls as the main character. Today, Dias has accumulated more than 9,000 books and has landed a book deal of her own and is now the author of Marley Dias Gets It Done!

Now with the support of GrassROOTS Community Foundation Marley has launched another campaign to send black girl books out globally to Ghana and Jamaica. The deadline is April 1st, 2020. If you would like to donate, check out the info above or visit this link https://grassrootscommunityfoundation.org/1000blackgirlbooks-relaunch/.

#Blackhistorymonth #bhm2020 #education #marleydias #womenempowerment #blackgirlsrock #blackgirlmagic

The city of Newark is a city full of depth, rich history, and has a major cultural and commercial impact on the world at large.

Did you know that Harriet Tubman often used tunnels in Newark, like the one located under the First Presbyterian Church on Broad Street, on her journey to bring enslaved people to freedom? #LivingBlackHistory #blackhistorymonth #BHM2020 #undergroundrailroad #newarkhistory #newark

Learn more here: https://www.njtvonline.org/news/video/nj-stops-along-the-underground-railroad/

post_text:
Did you know Black History Month used to only be a week long? Carter G. Woodson, historian and founder of “Negro History Week” selected the second week of February because it coincided with Fredrick Douglas (February 14) and Abraham Lincolns (February 12) birthdays. Negro History Week became Black History Month when it was officially recognized by President Gerald Ford in 1976.
